	<div class="spacer"></div>
	



			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="631">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Like Andrew Boyd [&ldquo;<a href="/article/4598">I Got Off the Beaten Path</a>,&rdquo; November 2011], when traveling I prefer the unplanned moments: purchasing a steaming chai from a cheeky street vendor in Bombay, or going off our planned route to visit with a Norwegian farmer.</p>

<p>Last year I took my three sons to Nepal for sixteen days. Their mother &mdash; whom I&rsquo;d fallen in love with in Nepal when we were both Peace Corps volunteers &mdash; had died two years prior. My intention was to expose my sons to the Nepal she and I had known and loved decades earlier, but my plan was stymied for a couple of reasons. First, <em>that </em>Nepal is no longer there. Second, I have multiple sclerosis. Though ambulatory on flat sidewalks, I found the arduous fifteen-hour walk to &ldquo;my&rdquo; old village impossible. The bucolic and unspoiled village, with its thatched roofs, verdant rice paddies, and views of distant Himalayan peaks, was beyond our reach.</p>

<p>And yet I did sit in a tea shop in Kathmandu, conversing in a language I hadn&rsquo;t spoken in decades, and at the Pashupati temple I watched smoke rise from funeral pyres. Did my boys ever &ldquo;get&rdquo; Nepal? Perhaps not in the way I&rsquo;d hoped. But what they did experience was worth the trip.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Peter Parsons<br>Chevy Chase, Maryland</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="621">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>After reading &ldquo;<a href="/article/4598">I Got off the Beaten Path</a>,&rdquo; by Andrew Boyd, I realized that it was only when Boyd took &ldquo;a few wrong turns&rdquo; that he found himself in the &ldquo;right&rdquo; place.</p>

<p>Presently out of work and struggling with the job market at sixty-eight, I have found myself looking for a situation in which I am comfortable. Boyd looked for a way out of the comfortable &ldquo;tourist bubble.&rdquo; Perhaps I must choose to leave the comfort of a regular job and explore the vast world &ldquo;outside the bubble.&rdquo;</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Vince Tolson<br>Richmond, Virginia</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="613">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I laughed in recognition at Andrew Boyd&rsquo;s &ldquo;<a href="/article/4598">I Got Off The Beaten Path (But So Did Everyone Else)</a>&rdquo; [November 2011], remembering my own attempts to be an &ldquo;anti-tourist&rdquo; in Asia and Europe. I always had a nagging sense that somewhere in the vicinity was a secret elite of &ldquo;anti-anti-tourists&rdquo; whose elevated state I might attain if only I could get far enough away from my own kind.</p>

<p>Boyd&rsquo;s essay sent me back to read Rob Keast&rsquo;s &ldquo;<a href="/article/4504">The Nature Trail Closest to My House</a>&rdquo; [February 2011], in which I recognized my older, possibly wiser self. After traveling to faraway places in search of escape from my drab, crass homeland, I am beginning to suspect that there is challenge and satisfaction enough in just trying to know my own backyard. But maybe that&rsquo;s a wisdom I could only have earned through the delights and disappointments of travel in the first place.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">L.J. Morin<br>Seattle, Washington</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
			</div>
			<a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor" class="cta-button b b-4 b-padding-tight small" data-label="Write Us A Letter!">Write Us A Letter!</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	

